          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A patient sustains a complete median nerve injury at the elbow. Most anterior fo</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient sustains a complete median nerve injury at the elbow. Most anterior forearm muscles are paralysed. Which superficial flexor retains normal function?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Pronator teres</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Pronator teres is supplied by the median nerve. It is the first muscle the nerve meets as it passes between its two heads.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Flexor carpi radialis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Flexor carpi radialis arises from the medial epicondyle and is supplied by the median nerve. It would be paralysed.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Flexor carpi ulnaris</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! FCU is the sole exception in the anterior compartment — it is supplied by the ulnar nerve, so it functions normally even when the median nerve is completely divided.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Palmaris longus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Palmaris longus, when present, is a median-nerve muscle. It would be paralysed along with the other superficial flexors.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "All anterior forearm muscles receive the median nerve or its anterior interosseous branch, except one: flexor carpi ulnaris is supplied by the ulnar nerve and would be the only superficial flexor still working after a median nerve injury at the elbow."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Of the eight anterior forearm muscles, all are supplied by the median nerve or its branch (the anterior interosseous nerve) except flexor carpi ulnaris, which receives the ulnar nerve."
                }
              ],
