          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A patient with a mid-shaft humerus fracture presents with wrist drop. Which find</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient with a mid-shaft humerus fracture presents with wrist drop. Which finding is expected on examination?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Loss of elbow extension (triceps paralysis)</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Triceps branches arise proximal to the spiral groove, so elbow extension is preserved despite radial nerve injury at this level.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Paralysis of all wrist and finger extensors with intact elbow extension</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! At the spiral groove, the radial nerve has already given off its triceps branches. Injury here paralyses every extensor distal to the groove while sparing elbow extension.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Finger drop only, with preserved wrist extension</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This pattern indicates posterior interosseous nerve (PIN) palsy, not radial nerve injury at the spiral groove. In PIN palsy, extensor carpi radialis longus is spared, preserving wrist extension.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sensory loss over the palm of the hand</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The radial nerve supplies sensation on the dorsum of the hand, not the palm. Palmar sensation is carried by the median and ulnar nerves.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Radial nerve injury at the spiral groove paralyses all wrist and finger extensors (causing wrist drop), but triceps is spared because its branches leave the radial nerve above the spiral groove. Contrast this with PIN palsy, where only finger extensors are lost and wrist extension is preserved."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. Wrist drop from a spiral groove fracture paralyses all wrist and finger extensors, but triceps is spared because its motor branches arise above the injury. This distinguishes it from PIN palsy, where wrist extension remains intact."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
