          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A 30-year-old woman presents with radial-sided wrist pain that worsens when lift</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A 30-year-old woman presents with radial-sided wrist pain that worsens when lifting her infant. The examiner asks her to tuck the thumb into a fist and ulnar-deviates the wrist, reproducing the pain. Which tendons are inflamed?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Abductor pollicis longus and extensor pollicis brevis</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! These two tendons share the first extensor compartment. Inflammation here is De Quervain's tenosynovitis, and the manoeuvre described is Finkelstein's test.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Extensor pollicis longus and extensor indicis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>EPL occupies the third compartment and extensor indicis the fourth. Inflammation in these compartments does not produce a positive Finkelstein's test.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Extensor carpi radialis longus and extensor carpi radialis brevis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>ECRL and ECRB lie in the second extensor compartment. Their tendinopathy causes dorsal wrist pain but is not associated with Finkelstein's test.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Flexor pollicis longus and flexor carpi radialis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>These are flexor tendons on the palmar side of the wrist. De Quervain's affects the extensor (dorsal) compartment at the radial styloid.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The manoeuvre described is Finkelstein's test, which stretches the tendons in the first extensor compartment — abductor pollicis longus and extensor pollicis brevis. Their inflammation at the radial styloid is De Quervain's tenosynovitis."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. De Quervain's tenosynovitis involves the first extensor compartment (APL and EPB). Finkelstein's test — ulnar deviation with the thumb tucked into a fist — stretches these tendons and reproduces the pain."
                }
              ],
